{"title_page": "Doja Cat", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Doja Cat\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Doja Cat Hot Pink Party2 (cropped).png\n| caption          = Doja Cat at the release party of ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' at the [[Museum of Sex]] in November 2019\n| birth_name       = Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1995|10|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|pop]]|[[Funk music|funk]]|[[Soul music|soul]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|keyboards|drums}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Kemosabe Records|Kemosabe]]}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{url|http://www.dojacat.com/}}\n}}\n'''Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini''' (born October 21, 1995),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/amalaratna_zandile_dlamini_born_1995_23577474|title=Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini, Born 10/21/1995 in California|website=[[California Birth Index]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305182114/https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/amala_zandile_dlamini_born_1995_23577474|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref> known professionally as '''Doja Cat''', is an American rapper, singer, songwriter and record producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2019-10-30/doja-cat-mooo-viral-hot-pink|title=Doja Cat went viral. Now what? A hip-hop meme star gets serious, sort of, for her second act|date=October 30, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> Born and raised in [[Los Angeles]], she signed a recording contract with [[RCA Records]] in 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rcarecords.com/artist/doja-cat/|title=Doja Cat|website=RCA Records}}</ref> subsequently releasing her debut [[extended play]], ''Purrr!'', and a series of singles, including \"Go to Town\" and \"So High\". In 2018, Doja Cat rose to prominence and internet fame with her single \"Mooo!\", which became a [[List of viral music videos|viral music video]] and ultimately \"set the tone for her career\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/how-doja-cats-mooo-set-the-tone-for-her-career-news.104785.html|title=How Doja Cat's \"Mooo!\" Set The Tone For Her Career|last=Blair|first=Robert|date=February 26, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDoja Cat released her debut studio album, ''[[Amala (album)|Amala]]'', in 2018 and a deluxe repackage in 2019, which included the single \"[[Tia Tamera]]\". She released the single \"[[Juicy (Doja Cat song)|Juicy]]\" in August 2019 which reached number 41 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], earning Doja Cat her first entry on the chart. Her second studio album, ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' (2019), entered the chart in over 10 countries including the US, Canada, Australia, the UK, Ireland and New Zealand. The album included the song \"[[Say So (Doja Cat song)|Say So]]\", which became popular on the video-sharing platform [[TikTok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2074773/doja-cat-say-so-tiktok-viral-stardom/franchises/the-week-in-pop/|title=Doja Cat Is Good At Making Pop Music And Even Better At Going Viral|last=DeVille|first=Chris|date=March 2, 2020|website=Stereogum|url-status=live|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> causing it to peak at number 9 in the US and number 7 in the UK, becoming her first song to enter the charts of various countries.\n\n==Early life==\nDlamini comes from an artistic family. Her father, Dumisani Dlamini, is a [[Demographics of South Africa|South African]] actor, composer and film producer of [[Zulu people|Zulu]] ethnicity best known for ''[[Sarafina! (film)|Sarafina!]]''<ref>Chrizelda Kekana, [https://www.timeslive.co.za/tshisa-live/tshisa-live/2017-10-25-dumisani-dlaminis-daughter-is-flying-the-flag-high-in-the-states/, \"Dumisani Dlamini's daughter is flying the flag high in the States\"], The Sunday Times/TimesLIVE (South Africa), October 25, 2017, retrieved March 26, 2018</ref> Her [[American Jews|Jewish American]] mother, Deborah Elizabeth Sawyer, is a painter, and her grandmother was an artist as well. She studied piano and danced as a child and teenager. Her brother would rap to her and she would listen which motivated her to develop her writing and rapping skills. As a teenager she used to listen to [[Gwen Stefani]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[Kelis]] and [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>[https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/01/doja-cat-rapper-interview/, \"Doja Cat Is Here to Stay With Whimsical Wordplay and Bars That Bite\u201d], XXL Magazine, retrieved March 15, 2020</ref> She has also cited [[Erykah Badu]], [[Jamiroquai]], [[PartyNextDoor]], and [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] as influences.<ref>[http://ninkimag.fr/jai-interviewe-doja-cat-la-nouvelle-princesse-du-rnb/, \"Doja Cat, La Nouvelle Sensation Hip-Hop/Soul\"], Ninkimag, retrieved March 26, 2018</ref><ref>[https://deecompress.wordpress.com/2016/03/08/who-is-doja-cat/, \"Who Is Doja Cat?], deecompress, March 8, 2016, retrieved March 26, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8544497/doja-cat-hot-pink-interview, \"Doja Cat Feels Liberated and More Focused Than Ever: 'I'm So Pumped For My Life Right Now'\"], Billboard, retrieved March 10, 2020</ref>\n\nDlamini explained that she got her stage name, \"Doja Cat\", from one of her cats and her favorite weed. She stated, \"I was heavily addicted to weed and weed culture, so when I began rapping I thought of the word 'doja' and how it sounds like a girl's name.\"<ref>Chrizelda Kekana, [https://www.popsugar.com/celebrity/photo-gallery/46953473/embed/46953490/p, \"10 Things You Probably Didn't Know About Doja Cat \u2014 Including the Origin of Her Name\"], PopSugar, December 26, 2019, retrieved February 27, 2020</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2013\u20132017: ''Purrr!'' and collaborations===\nDoja Cat released her debut single \"So High\" on the streaming platform [[SoundCloud]] in 2013, coming to prominence that year when she later signed to [[RCA Records]] with a joint venture deal with [[Kemosabe Records]]. She signed to them in late 2013 but the deal was finalised in early 2014. She released her debut EP, ''Purrr!'' (described as \"spacey, eastern-influenced R&B\" by ''[[The Fader]]'') later that year.<ref>David Turner, [http://www.thefader.com/2014/08/05/la-singer-doja-cat-drops-her-new-ep-empurrrem \"LA Singer Doja Cat Drops Her New EP Purrr!\"], ;ater that year. ''The Fader'', August 5, 2014, retrieved March 24, 2018</ref> Premiering the video for the single \"So High\", ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' described her as an \"18-year-old psychedelic prodigy\".<ref>Adelle Platon, [https://www.vibe.com/2014/03/premiere-doja-cat-so-high-video-watch/ \"Premiere: Doja Cat 'So High' Video\"] |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Vibe'', March 25, 2014, retrieved March 24, 2018</ref> The song was featured on the TV series ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]'' soundtrack, on the third episode of the first season. \"No Police\" was released as the second single from ''Purrr!''. She started releasing more music on SoundCloud and YouTube as she started gaining more attention. In mid-2015 Doja was also signed to [[OG Maco]]'s label, OGG. Following this signing, the two artists collaborated on \"Monster\" off of Maco's 2017 album, \"Children of the Rage\". She had also started collaborating with other artists, such as [[Elliphant]], Hellboy, Skoolie Escobar, Pregnant Boy, and frumhere. Doja released the single \"Candy\" on September 9, 2016. The song gained mainstream traction over three years later due to the use in viral videos on social media app [[TikTok]], and charted at number 86 on the Billboard Hot 100 in December 2019. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2019-12-07|title=The Hot 100 Chart \u2013 Week of December 7, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> On July 13, 2017, Doja Cat was featured on L8LOOMER's single \"Right Side\". The song was then featured on L8LOOMER's debut album ''Soulm8s'' in 2018. During this time, she also released multiple songs that she produced and wrote by herself on her SoundCloud account exclusively.\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Amala'' and ''Hot Pink''===\nOn February 1, 2018, she released the single \"Roll with Us\", which was dubbed as the debut single off her debut studio album. On March 9, 2018, she released the second single from her upcoming album, \"Go to Town\", with an accompanying music video released the same day on her YouTube channel. As of March 2020, the music video has reached 29 million views on the platform. On March 30, 2018, Doja Cat's first full-length debut studio album ''[[Amala (album)|Amala]]'' was released. On August 10, 2018, Doja Cat released a song titled \"Mooo!\" on YouTube. The single is a [[novelty song]] with absurdist lyrics where she fantasizes about being a [[cow]].<ref name=\"Ritzen\">{{cite web|author=Ritzen, Stacey|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/doja-cat-im-a-cow-homophobic-slurs/|title=Doja Cat Of 'I'm A Cow' Fame Tries To Defend Homophobic Comments In Bad Tweet|work=[[Daily Dot]]|publisher=[[Complex Media]] |date=August 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> Made with the intention of doubling as a [[Internet meme|meme]], the song quickly became a [[List of viral music videos|viral music video]]. The video gathered attention and praise from popular artists such as [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Katy Perry]] and [[Chris Brown]].<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8470340/doja-cat-mooo-chance-the-rapper-katy-perry-interview \"Doja Cat Talks the Viral Success of 'Mooo,' Getting a Chance the Rapper Co-Sign & Lessons Learned From Debut LP 'Amala'\"], ''Billboard'', August 15, 2018, retrieved August 17, 2018</ref> On August 31, she released the single version of \"Mooo!\". It inspired several jokes and [[meme]]s while the accompanying [[music video]] acquired over 65 million views since it was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on August 10.<ref name=\"Ritzen\"/><ref name=\"Peters\">{{cite web |author=Peters, Micah|title=The Rapid Rise and Fall of Doja Cat in the Era of \"Cancel\" Culture|url=https://www.theringer.com/music/2018/9/3/17806934/doja-cat-mooo-homophobic-tweets-asian-doll-yung-miami-city-girls-cancel-culture|work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|publisher=The Ringer|date=September 3, 2018 |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Doja Cat released her single \"[[Tia Tamera]]\" featuring [[Rico Nasty]], which is the leading single to the deluxe edition of her debut album [[Amala (Doja Cat album)|''Amala'']]. The following month, she was featured on the hit YouTube channel Colorsklll with a performance of \"Juicy\", a song taken from the repackage of the album. On August 15, 2019, Doja Cat released a remix of \"[[Juicy (Doja Cat song)|Juicy]]\", featuring [[Tyga]] with an accompanying music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/08/doja-cat-tyga-juicy-remix-video|title=Doja Cat Recruits Tyga for \"Juicy\" Remix Video|website=Complex}}</ref> The song debuted at 83 and peaked at 41 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it her first song to reach that chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/chart-climber-doja-cat-moves-past-the-mooo-meme-with-juicy|title=Chart Climber: Doja Cat Moves Past The Meme With \"Juicy\"|website=Genius}}</ref> The success of \"Juicy\" also helped her album ''Amala'' to chart on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at number 162. On October 26, 2019, she released another single called \"Rules\". On November 7, 2019, Doja Cat released her second full-length album ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' to generally favorable reviews. It peaked at number 17 on the ''Billboard'' 200. On December 15, 2019, Doja Cat announced that she had contributed a song to [[Birds of Prey: The Album|the soundtrack]] of the superhero film ''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]'' in which \"Boss Bitch\" was released as the album's third single on January 23, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/doja-cat-birds-of-prey-song-soundtrack-harley-quinn-film-margot-robbie-2588547|title=Doja Cat has recorded a new song for the 'Birds of Prey' film|date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2020, Doja Cat's song \"[[Say So (Doja Cat song)|Say So]]\" was sent to radio becoming the fifth single off of her album ''Hot Pink''.<ref name =\"US Date\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|title=Top 40/M Future Releases|website=All Access Music Group|accessdate=January 24, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123070408/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archivedate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> The song was originally released alongside the album in November 2019, but the song gained popularity through social media, particularly from TikTok.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last1=Mamo |first1=Heran |title=Here Are the Lyrics to Doja Cat's 'Say So' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8548599/doja-cat-say-so-lyrics |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Doja Cat performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' on February 26, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/doja-cat-delivers-sultry-say-so-performance-for-tonight-show-news.104862.html|title=Doja Cat Delivers Fun & Sultry \"Say So\" Performance For \"Tonight Show\"|website=HotNewHipHop|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> The next day, Doja Cat released the music video for the song, directed by [[Hannah Lux Davis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/02/27/doja-cat-say-so-video/|title=Doja Cat Goes Disco in 'Say So' Video|website=Rap-Up|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> \"Say So\" so far has peaked at number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100]], becoming Doja Cat's first top 10 single. <ref name=\"Hot 100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Doja+Cat&chartcode=HSI|title=Chart Search: Doja Cat, Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>The music video includes Haley Sharpe, the TikToker that created the dance for \"Say So\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/billboardcharts/status/1234602502911336449|title=.@DojaCat on this week's #Hot100: #33, Say So (new peak; first week in the top 40) #55, Juicy w/ @Tyga|first=Billboard|last=Charts|date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, 2020, Doja Cat is set to embark on the [[Hot Pink Tour]], to promote her second studio album. The tour will have fifteen shows spanning across North America, including two Coachella performances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/2/25/21152519/doja-cat-hot-pink-tour|title=Doja Cat announces tour in support of 'Hot Pink'|last=Moorwood|first=Victoria|date=February 25, 2020|website=REVOLT|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/sounddiego/coachella-announces-2020-lineup-travis-scott-rage-against-the-machine-frank-ocean-indio-thom-yorke-lana-del-rey/2237434/|title=Coachella Announces 2020 Lineup|website=NBC 7 San Diego|language=en-US|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn September 2018, Doja Cat sparked controversy on [[social media]] when her [[Twitter]] account history revealed the usage of [[homophobic]] slurs. In a [[twitter#Tweets|tweet]] dating back to 2015, Doja Cat used the word \"[[Faggot (slang)|faggot]]\" to describe hip-hop artists [[Tyler, the Creator]] and [[Earl Sweatshirt]], members of the musical collective [[Odd Future]].<ref name=\"Peters\"/> Doja Cat initially defended her past homophobic remarks.<ref name=\"Bote\"/> She stated, \"I called a couple people faggots when I was in high school in 2015 does this mean I don't deserve support? I've said faggot roughly like 15 thousand times in my life. Does saying faggot mean you hate [[Gay|gay people]]? I don't think I hate gay people. Gay is ok.\"<ref name=\"Bote\">{{cite web|author=Bote, Joshua|title=Doja Cat Comes Under Fire for Defending Homophobic Language in Tweet| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8472803/doja-cat-under-fire-defending-homophobic-language-tweet| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=August 29, 2018 | accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> Her response was met by even more backlash, including a critical tweet from ''[[Will and Grace]]'' actress [[Debra Messing]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Montgomery, Sarah Jasmine|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/08/doja-cat-criticized-attempt-explain-past-use-homophobic-slur|title=Doja Cat Criticized Over Attempt to Explain Her Past Use of a Homophobic Slur |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] | date=August 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> In her statement, Messing expressed disappointment with Doja for defending past ignorance and implored her to use her fame and platform for good. Doja Cat has since issued a series of apologies for her derogatory words and deleted her tweets.<ref name=\"Bote\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Doja Cat discography}}\n*''[[Amala (album)|Amala]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' (2019)\n\n== Tours ==\n===Headlining===\n* Purrr! Tour (2014-2015)\n* Amala Spring Tour (2017-2018)\n* Amala Fall Tour (2018-2019)\n* [[Hot Pink Tour]] (2020; {{small|postponed due to [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Doja Cat}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:African-American Jews]]\n[[Category:African-American female rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American female rappers]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish rappers]]\n[[Category:Jewish singers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Doja Cat\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Doja Cat Hot Pink Party2 (cropped).png\n| caption          = Doja Cat at the release party of ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' at the [[Museum of Sex]] in November 2019\n| birth_name       = Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1995|10|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|pop]]|[[Funk music|funk]]|[[Soul music|soul]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|keyboards|drums}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Kemosabe Records|Kemosabe]]}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{url|http://www.dojacat.com/}}\n}}\n'''Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini''' (born October 21, 1995),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/amalaratna_zandile_dlamini_born_1995_23577474|title=Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini, Born 10/21/1995 in California|website=[[California Birth Index]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305182114/https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/amala_zandile_dlamini_born_1995_23577474|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref> known professionally as '''Doja Cat''', is an American rapper, singer, songwriter and record producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2019-10-30/doja-cat-mooo-viral-hot-pink|title=Doja Cat went viral. Now what? A hip-hop meme star gets serious, sort of, for her second act|date=October 30, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> Born and raised in [[Los Angeles]], she signed a recording contract with [[RCA Records]] in 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rcarecords.com/artist/doja-cat/|title=Doja Cat|website=RCA Records}}</ref> subsequently releasing her debut [[extended play]], ''Purrr!'', and a series of singles, including \"Go to Town\" and \"So High\". In 2018, Doja Cat rose to prominence and internet fame with her single \"Mooo!\", which became a [[List of viral music videos|viral music video]] and ultimately \"set the tone for her career\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/how-doja-cats-mooo-set-the-tone-for-her-career-news.104785.html|title=How Doja Cat's \"Mooo!\" Set The Tone For Her Career|last=Blair|first=Robert|date=February 26, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDoja Cat released her debut studio album, ''[[Amala (album)|Amala]]'', in 2018 and a deluxe repackage in 2019, which included the single \"[[Tia Tamera]]\". She released the single \"[[Juicy (Doja Cat song)|Juicy]]\" in August 2019 which reached number 41 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], earning Doja Cat her first entry on the chart. Her second studio album, ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' (2019), entered the chart in over 10 countries including the US, Canada, Australia, the UK, Ireland and New Zealand. The album included the song \"[[Say So (Doja Cat song)|Say So]]\", which became popular on the video-sharing platform [[TikTok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2074773/doja-cat-say-so-tiktok-viral-stardom/franchises/the-week-in-pop/|title=Doja Cat Is Good At Making Pop Music And Even Better At Going Viral|last=DeVille|first=Chris|date=March 2, 2020|website=Stereogum|url-status=live|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> causing it to peak at number 9 in the US and number 7 in the UK, becoming her first song to enter the charts of various countries.\n\n==Early life==\nDlamini comes from an artistic family. Her father, Dumisani Dlamini, is a [[Demographics of South Africa|South African]] actor, composer and film producer of [[Zulu people|Zulu]] ethnicity best known for ''[[Sarafina! (film)|Sarafina!]]''<ref>Chrizelda Kekana, [https://www.timeslive.co.za/tshisa-live/tshisa-live/2017-10-25-dumisani-dlaminis-daughter-is-flying-the-flag-high-in-the-states/, \"Dumisani Dlamini's daughter is flying the flag high in the States\"], The Sunday Times/TimesLIVE (South Africa), October 25, 2017, retrieved March 26, 2018</ref> Her [[American Jews|Jewish American]] mother, Deborah Elizabeth Sawyer, is a painter, and her grandmother was an artist as well. She studied piano and danced as a child and teenager. Her brother would rap to her and she would listen which motivated her to develop her writing and rapping skills. As a teenager she used to listen to [[Gwen Stefani]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[Kelis]] and [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>[https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/01/doja-cat-rapper-interview/, \"Doja Cat Is Here to Stay With Whimsical Wordplay and Bars That Bite\u201d], XXL Magazine, retrieved March 15, 2020</ref> She has also cited [[Erykah Badu]], [[Jamiroquai]], [[PartyNextDoor]], and [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] as influences.<ref>[http://ninkimag.fr/jai-interviewe-doja-cat-la-nouvelle-princesse-du-rnb/, \"Doja Cat, La Nouvelle Sensation Hip-Hop/Soul\"], Ninkimag, retrieved March 26, 2018</ref><ref>[https://deecompress.wordpress.com/2016/03/08/who-is-doja-cat/, \"Who Is Doja Cat?], deecompress, March 8, 2016, retrieved March 26, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8544497/doja-cat-hot-pink-interview, \"Doja Cat Feels Liberated and More Focused Than Ever: 'I'm So Pumped For My Life Right Now'\"], Billboard, retrieved March 10, 2020</ref>\n\nDlamini explained that she got her stage name, \"Doja Cat\", from one of her cats and her favorite weed. She stated, \"I was heavily addicted to weed and weed culture, so when I began rapping I thought of the word 'doja' and how it sounds like a girl's name.\"<ref>Chrizelda Kekana, [https://www.popsugar.com/celebrity/photo-gallery/46953473/embed/46953490/p, \"10 Things You Probably Didn't Know About Doja Cat \u2014 Including the Origin of Her Name\"], PopSugar, December 26, 2019, retrieved February 27, 2020</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2013\u20132017: ''Purrr!'' and collaborations===\nDoja Cat released her debut single \"So High\" on the streaming platform [[SoundCloud]] in 2013, coming to prominence that year when she later signed to [[RCA Records]] with a joint venture deal with [[Kemosabe Records]]. She signed to them in late 2013 but the deal was finalised in early 2014. She released her debut EP, ''Purrr!'' (described as \"spacey, eastern-influenced R&B\" by ''[[The Fader]]'') later that year.<ref>David Turner, [http://www.thefader.com/2014/08/05/la-singer-doja-cat-drops-her-new-ep-empurrrem \"LA Singer Doja Cat Drops Her New EP Purrr!\"], ;ater that year. ''The Fader'', August 5, 2014, retrieved March 24, 2018</ref> Premiering the video for the single \"So High\", ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' described her as an \"18-year-old psychedelic prodigy\".<ref>Adelle Platon, [https://www.vibe.com/2014/03/premiere-doja-cat-so-high-video-watch/ \"Premiere: Doja Cat 'So High' Video\"] |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Vibe'', March 25, 2014, retrieved March 24, 2018</ref> The song was featured on the TV series ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]'' soundtrack, on the third episode of the first season. \"No Police\" was released as the second single from ''Purrr!''. She started releasing more music on SoundCloud and YouTube as she started gaining more attention. In mid-2015 Doja was also signed to [[OG Maco]]'s label, OGG. Following this signing, the two artists collaborated on \"Monster\" off of Maco's 2017 album, \"Children of the Rage\". She had also started collaborating with other artists, such as [[Elliphant]], Hellboy, Skoolie Escobar, Pregnant Boy, and frumhere. Doja released the single \"Candy\" on September 9, 2016. The song gained mainstream traction over three years later due to the use in viral videos on social media app [[TikTok]], and charted at number 86 on the Billboard Hot 100 in December 2019. On July 13, 2017, Doja Cat was featured on L8LOOMER's single \"Right Side\". The song was then featured on L8LOOMER's debut album ''Soulm8s'' in 2018. During this time, she also released multiple songs that she produced and wrote by herself on her SoundCloud account exclusively.\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Amala'' and ''Hot Pink''===\nOn February 1, 2018, she released the single \"Roll with Us\", which was dubbed as the debut single off her debut studio album. On March 9, 2018, she released the second single from her upcoming album, \"Go to Town\", with an accompanying music video released the same day on her YouTube channel. As of March 2020, the music video has reached 29 million views on the platform. On March 30, 2018, Doja Cat's first full-length debut studio album ''[[Amala (album)|Amala]]'' was released. On August 10, 2018, Doja Cat released a song titled \"Mooo!\" on YouTube. The single is a [[novelty song]] with absurdist lyrics where she fantasizes about being a [[cow]].<ref name=\"Ritzen\">{{cite web|author=Ritzen, Stacey|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/doja-cat-im-a-cow-homophobic-slurs/|title=Doja Cat Of 'I'm A Cow' Fame Tries To Defend Homophobic Comments In Bad Tweet|work=[[Daily Dot]]|publisher=[[Complex Media]] |date=August 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> Made with the intention of doubling as a [[Internet meme|meme]], the song quickly became a [[List of viral music videos|viral music video]]. The video gathered attention and praise from popular artists such as [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Katy Perry]] and [[Chris Brown]].<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8470340/doja-cat-mooo-chance-the-rapper-katy-perry-interview \"Doja Cat Talks the Viral Success of 'Mooo,' Getting a Chance the Rapper Co-Sign & Lessons Learned From Debut LP 'Amala'\"], ''Billboard'', August 15, 2018, retrieved August 17, 2018</ref> On August 31, she released the single version of \"Mooo!\". It inspired several jokes and [[meme]]s while the accompanying [[music video]] acquired over 65 million views since it was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on August 10.<ref name=\"Ritzen\"/><ref name=\"Peters\">{{cite web |author=Peters, Micah|title=The Rapid Rise and Fall of Doja Cat in the Era of \"Cancel\" Culture|url=https://www.theringer.com/music/2018/9/3/17806934/doja-cat-mooo-homophobic-tweets-asian-doll-yung-miami-city-girls-cancel-culture|work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|publisher=The Ringer|date=September 3, 2018 |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Doja Cat released her single \"[[Tia Tamera]]\" featuring [[Rico Nasty]], which is the leading single to the deluxe edition of her debut album [[Amala (Doja Cat album)|''Amala'']]. The following month, she was featured on the hit YouTube channel Colorsklll with a performance of \"Juicy\", a song taken from the repackage of the album. On August 15, 2019, Doja Cat released a remix of \"[[Juicy (Doja Cat song)|Juicy]]\", featuring [[Tyga]] with an accompanying music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/08/doja-cat-tyga-juicy-remix-video|title=Doja Cat Recruits Tyga for \"Juicy\" Remix Video|website=Complex}}</ref> The song debuted at 83 and peaked at 41 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it her first song to reach that chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/chart-climber-doja-cat-moves-past-the-mooo-meme-with-juicy|title=Chart Climber: Doja Cat Moves Past The Meme With \"Juicy\"|website=Genius}}</ref> The success of \"Juicy\" also helped her album ''Amala'' to chart on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at number 162. On October 26, 2019, she released another single called \"Rules\". On November 7, 2019, Doja Cat released her second full-length album ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' to generally favorable reviews. It peaked at number 17 on the ''Billboard'' 200. On December 15, 2019, Doja Cat announced that she had contributed a song to [[Birds of Prey: The Album|the soundtrack]] of the superhero film ''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]'' in which \"Boss Bitch\" was released as the album's third single on January 23, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/doja-cat-birds-of-prey-song-soundtrack-harley-quinn-film-margot-robbie-2588547|title=Doja Cat has recorded a new song for the 'Birds of Prey' film|date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2020, Doja Cat's song \"[[Say So (Doja Cat song)|Say So]]\" was sent to radio becoming the fifth single off of her album ''Hot Pink''.<ref name =\"US Date\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|title=Top 40/M Future Releases|website=All Access Music Group|accessdate=January 24, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123070408/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archivedate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> The song was originally released alongside the album in November 2019, but the song gained popularity through social media, particularly from TikTok.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last1=Mamo |first1=Heran |title=Here Are the Lyrics to Doja Cat's 'Say So' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8548599/doja-cat-say-so-lyrics |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Doja Cat performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' on February 26, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/doja-cat-delivers-sultry-say-so-performance-for-tonight-show-news.104862.html|title=Doja Cat Delivers Fun & Sultry \"Say So\" Performance For \"Tonight Show\"|website=HotNewHipHop|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> The next day, Doja Cat released the music video for the song, directed by [[Hannah Lux Davis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/02/27/doja-cat-say-so-video/|title=Doja Cat Goes Disco in 'Say So' Video|website=Rap-Up|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> \"Say So\" so far has peaked at number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100]], becoming Doja Cat's first top 10 single. <ref name=\"Hot 100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Doja+Cat&chartcode=HSI|title=Chart Search: Doja Cat, Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>The music video includes Haley Sharpe, the TikToker that created the dance for \"Say So\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/billboardcharts/status/1234602502911336449|title=.@DojaCat on this week's #Hot100: #33, Say So (new peak; first week in the top 40) #55, Juicy w/ @Tyga|first=Billboard|last=Charts|date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, 2020, Doja Cat is set to embark on the [[Hot Pink Tour]], to promote her second studio album. The tour will have fifteen shows spanning across North America, including two Coachella performances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/2/25/21152519/doja-cat-hot-pink-tour|title=Doja Cat announces tour in support of 'Hot Pink'|last=Moorwood|first=Victoria|date=February 25, 2020|website=REVOLT|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/sounddiego/coachella-announces-2020-lineup-travis-scott-rage-against-the-machine-frank-ocean-indio-thom-yorke-lana-del-rey/2237434/|title=Coachella Announces 2020 Lineup|website=NBC 7 San Diego|language=en-US|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn September 2018, Doja Cat sparked controversy on [[social media]] when her [[Twitter]] account history revealed the usage of [[homophobic]] slurs. In a [[twitter#Tweets|tweet]] dating back to 2015, Doja Cat used the word \"[[Faggot (slang)|faggot]]\" to describe hip-hop artists [[Tyler, the Creator]] and [[Earl Sweatshirt]], members of the musical collective [[Odd Future]].<ref name=\"Peters\"/> Doja Cat initially defended her past homophobic remarks.<ref name=\"Bote\"/> She stated, \"I called a couple people faggots when I was in high school in 2015 does this mean I don't deserve support? I've said faggot roughly like 15 thousand times in my life. Does saying faggot mean you hate [[Gay|gay people]]? I don't think I hate gay people. Gay is ok.\"<ref name=\"Bote\">{{cite web|author=Bote, Joshua|title=Doja Cat Comes Under Fire for Defending Homophobic Language in Tweet| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8472803/doja-cat-under-fire-defending-homophobic-language-tweet| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=August 29, 2018 | accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> Her response was met by even more backlash, including a critical tweet from ''[[Will and Grace]]'' actress [[Debra Messing]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Montgomery, Sarah Jasmine|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/08/doja-cat-criticized-attempt-explain-past-use-homophobic-slur|title=Doja Cat Criticized Over Attempt to Explain Her Past Use of a Homophobic Slur |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] | date=August 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> In her statement, Messing expressed disappointment with Doja for defending past ignorance and implored her to use her fame and platform for good. Doja Cat has since issued a series of apologies for her derogatory words and deleted her tweets.<ref name=\"Bote\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Doja Cat discography}}\n*''[[Amala (album)|Amala]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' (2019)\n\n== Tours ==\n===Headlining===\n* Purrr! Tour (2014-2015)\n* Amala Spring Tour (2017-2018)\n* Amala Fall Tour (2018-2019)\n* [[Hot Pink Tour]] (2020; {{small|postponed due to [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Doja Cat}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:African-American Jews]]\n[[Category:African-American female rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American female rappers]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish rappers]]\n[[Category:Jewish singers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Tease Pillar", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2013\u20132017: Purrr! and collaborations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doja_Cat"}
{"title_page": "Francesco P\u00e9nna", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}\n\n'''Francesco P\u00e9nna''' (April 9, 1865 \u2013 1927)<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/francesco-penna/ Short Bio in Treccani Encyclopedia.]</ref> was an [[Italy|Italian]] sculptor.\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Naples]]. He completed his studies at the [[Accademia di Belle Arti di Napoli|Institute of Fine Arts]] of Naples, where he won a variety of contests, and dedicated himself to industrial sculptural art in [[terra cotta]] and ceramic, working mostly from Rome and Milan. He garnered prizes for this at the Exhibition of [[Melbourne, Australia]], and at [[Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires, Argentina]]. At the first of these Exhibitions he sent large chalices in ceramic and terracotta. To [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] he sent a small sculpture depicting ''The Orphan of Casamicciola'' which won a gold medal. Many of his works were sold in Buenos Aires. His ''Alcestis Revived'' (1912) is in the Galleria d'arte Moderna of [[Milan]]. He also made portraits and funeral monuments.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Zz0bAAAAYAAJ Dizionario degli Artisti Italiani Viventi: pittori, scultori, e Architetti.], by Angelo de Gubernatis. Tipe dei Successori Le Monnier, 1889, page 365.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penna, Francesco}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Naples]]\n[[Category:Italian sculptors]]\n[[Category:Italian male sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:Accademia di Belle Arti di Napoli alumni]]\n\n\n{{Italy-sculptor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}\n\n'''Francesco P\u00e9nna''' (April 9, 1865 \u2013 1927)<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/francesco-penna/ Short Bio in Treccani Encyclopedia.]</ref> was an [[Italy|Italian]] sculptor.\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Naples]]. He completed his studies at the [[Accademia di Belle Arti di Napoli|Institute of Fine Arts]] of Naples, where he won a variety of contests, and dedicated himself to industrial sculptural art in [[terra cotta]] and ceramic, working mostly from Rome and Milan. He garnered prizes for this at the Exhibition of [[Melbourne, Australia]], and at [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina. At the first of these Exhibitions he sent large chalices in ceramic and terracotta. To [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] he sent a small sculpture depicting ''The Orphan of Casamicciola'' which won a gold medal. Many of his works were sold in Buenos Aires. His ''Alcestis Revived'' (1912) is in the Galleria d'arte Moderna of [[Milan]]. He also made portraits and funeral monuments.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Zz0bAAAAYAAJ Dizionario degli Artisti Italiani Viventi: pittori, scultori, e Architetti.], by Angelo de Gubernatis. Tipe dei Successori Le Monnier, 1889, page 365.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penna, Francesco}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Naples]]\n[[Category:Italian sculptors]]\n[[Category:Italian male sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:Accademia di Belle Arti di Napoli alumni]]\n\n\n{{Italy-sculptor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DarkerBlue599", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing interlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francesco_P%C3%A9nna"}
{"title_page": "Clayton County commuter rail", "text_new": "{{Clayton County commuter rail}}\n'''Clayton County commuter rail''' is a planned [[commuter rail]] line traversing [[Clayton County, Georgia]] and connecting with the [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] [[rapid transit]] system at [[East Point station]].\n\nAfter Clayton County joined the MARTA system in 2014, MARTA began studying alternatives for high-capacity transit through the county. Commuter rail was selected as the locally preferred alternative in 2018.\n\nConstruction of initial phase beginning as early as 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/More/Projects/Planning_Projects/Clayton_County/Clayton%20County%20Fact%20Sheetd%20060418.pdf|title=Clayton County Transit Initiative Fact Sheet|last=|first=|date=Spring 2018|website=www.itsmarta.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 02, 2020}}</ref> Operation between [[Morrow, Georgia|Morrow]]/[[Southlake Mall (Atlanta)|Southlake Mall]] and MARTA's [[East Point station|East Point Station]] in service by 2030.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/boc-set-to-vote-on-marta-15th-contract-amendment/article_9872dcec-3c94-11ea-92f1-83ffa5a78b97.html|title=BOC set to vote on MARTA 15th contract amendment|last=robin.kemp@news-daily.com|first=Robin Kemp|website=Clayton News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Planned extensions to [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]] and [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] will be implemented in a phased approach. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://45tkhs2ch4042kf51f1akcju-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/fifteenthamendment12.11.2019.pdf|title=FIFTEENTH AMENDMENT TO RAPID TRANSIT CONTRACT AND ASSISTANCE AGREEMENT|last=|first=|date=December 11, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning by GDOT===\n{{Main|Georgia Rail Passenger Program}}\nPotential routes for commuter rail service in metropolitan Atlanta were studied by the [[Georgia Department of Transportation]] (GDOT) beginning in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |title=GDOT - Commuter Rail |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021218062539/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |archive-date=December 18, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Eventually, plans for a system of seven lines radiating out from [[Five Points, Atlanta]] were developed and dubbed the [[Georgia Rail Passenger Program]]. The program included one line running through Clayton County and terminating in [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dot.ga.gov/InvestSmart/Rail/Documents/GRPPFactSheet2006.pdf |title=Georgia Rail Passenger Program 2006 Fact Sheet |access-date=December 18, 2019 | df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy 2004, GDOT's effort had concentrated on two lines terminating in [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] (a shortened Macon line) and [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |title=Office of Intermodal Program--Rail Index |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040906055758/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |archive-date=September 6, 2004|url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the time, the planned Lovejoy line was anticipated to open in 2006 and $106 million in federal funding was earmarked for the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |title=Lovejoy Commuter Rail fact sheet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040302014011/http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |archive-date=September 6, 2004 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Clayton County Board of Commissioners was supportive of the line, asking the state government to advance the plan.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Corriher |first1= Billy |url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/county-requests-atlanta-lovejoy-rail-line/article_7cf4fb09-0fe6-52b9-a3f5-911cb62ade25.html |title=County requests Atlanta-Lovejoy rail line |date=December 16, 2003 |access-date=December 18, 2019 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after years of inaction from the state on the project, then-governor [[Sonny Perdue]] announced his support for the Lovejoy line. This was speculated to be partially due to the project being in danger of losing its federal funding because of a lack of progress.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Saporta |first1= Maria |url=http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |title=At last, Gov. Perdue on board for commuter rail |date=June 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522085502/http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Due to further inaction, the federal government withdrew the funds it had previously appropriated for the project in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simmons |first1=Andria |url=https://www.governing.com/news/headlines/mct-commuter-rail-atlanta.html |title=Feds Take Back Millions in Unused Money for Atlanta Commuter Rail |date=July 11, 2014 |access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Planning by MARTA===\nOn July 5, 2014, the Clayton County Board of Commissioners approved a contract with [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] to extend service to the county by a margin of 3-1, financed by a 1% sales tax. Fulton and DeKalb county leaders approved the expansion and on November 4, 2014, Clayton County residents approved the 1% sales tax to join MARTA. The contract reserves half of the collected tax revenue for the development of rail transit in the county, with the other half funding local bus service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714154106/http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot| archive-date=July 14, 2014 |title=Clayton approves MARTA contract for November ballot |publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta |author=John Ruch |date=2014-07-05}}</ref>\n\nCommuter rail was selected in 2018 as the locally preferred alternative of transit mode along the corridor,<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice >{{cite news |last1=Saporta |first1=Maria |title=Commuter rail is MARTA\u2019s choice for Clayton County |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2018/07/13/commuter-rail-is-marta-s-choice-for-clayton-county.html |accessdate=13 July 2018 |agency=Atlanta Business Journal |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> which was later approved by the MARTA Board of Directors.<ref name=MARTAapproves>{{cite news |last1=Wickert |first1=David |title=MARTA approves plans for Clayton County commuter train |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/marta-approves-plans-for-clayton-county-commuter-train/TGCcz6JGlUOxvzLzQTtUnJ/ |accessdate=8 December 2018 |agency=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, all four MARTA jurisdictions passed the 15th Amendment to the Rapid Transit Contract and Assistance Agreement (RTCAA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itsmarta.com/jurisdictions-pass-15th-amendment.aspx|title=MARTA|website=www.itsmarta.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The amendment enables MARTA to proceed with expansion projects in Clayton County. Exhibit D  Exhibit D, Clayton County System Implantation Plan details several high-capacity transit projects including commuter rail (CRT) and bus rapid transit (BRT).<ref name=\":1\" /> MARTA has committed to continued planning and design on the Clayton County Commuter Rail project, which will stretch 22 miles from East Point Station to Lovejoy, with the first phase (about 11 miles) from East Point to Morrow/Southlake Mall up and running by 2030.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Route==\nThe line follows the existing [[Norfolk Southern]] [[right of way]] from [[East Point station]] to [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] in southern Clayton County, a distance of {{convert|22|mi}}.<ref name=MARTAapproves /> MARTA is negotiating with Norfolk Southern to install tracks in their right of way, adjacent to the freight line.<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice />\n\nOne version of the proposal calls for stations at [[Hapeville, Georgia|Hapeville]], [[Mountain View, Georgia|Mountain View]], [[Forest Park, Georgia|Forest Park]], [[Fort Gillem]], [[Clayton State University]], [[Morrow, Georgia|Morrow]] and [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]]. A station in [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] is also proposed, which would open as a later phase.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |title=MARTA Proposed Clayton County Service in 2025 |access-date=November 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052952/http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.itsmarta.com/clayton-county-overview.aspx MARTA overiew]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MARTA Nav}}\n[[Category:Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Clayton County commuter rail}}\n'''Clayton County commuter rail''' is a planned [[commuter rail]] line traversing [[Clayton County, Georgia]] and connecting with the [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] [[rapid transit]] system at [[East Point station]].\n\nAfter Clayton County joined the MARTA system in 2014, MARTA began studying alternatives for high-capacity transit through the county. Commuter rail was selected as the locally preferred alternative in 2018.\n\nThe line may break ground in 2023, with revenue service between [[Morrow, Georgia|Morrow]]/[[Southlake Mall (Atlanta)|Southlake Mall]] and MARTA's [[East Point station|East Point Station]] by 2030.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/boc-set-to-vote-on-marta-15th-contract-amendment/article_9872dcec-3c94-11ea-92f1-83ffa5a78b97.html|title=BOC set to vote on MARTA 15th contract amendment|last=robin.kemp@news-daily.com|first=Robin Kemp|website=Clayton News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Planned extensions to [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]] and [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] will be implemented in a phased approach. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://45tkhs2ch4042kf51f1akcju-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/fifteenthamendment12.11.2019.pdf|title=FIFTEENTH AMENDMENT TO RAPID TRANSIT CONTRACT AND ASSISTANCE AGREEMENT|last=|first=|date=December 11, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning by GDOT===\n{{Main|Georgia Rail Passenger Program}}\nPotential routes for commuter rail service in metropolitan Atlanta were studied by the [[Georgia Department of Transportation]] (GDOT) beginning in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |title=GDOT - Commuter Rail |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021218062539/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |archive-date=December 18, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Eventually, plans for a system of seven lines radiating out from [[Five Points, Atlanta]] were developed and dubbed the [[Georgia Rail Passenger Program]]. The program included one line running through Clayton County and terminating in [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dot.ga.gov/InvestSmart/Rail/Documents/GRPPFactSheet2006.pdf |title=Georgia Rail Passenger Program 2006 Fact Sheet |access-date=December 18, 2019 | df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy 2004, GDOT's effort had concentrated on two lines terminating in [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] (a shortened Macon line) and [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |title=Office of Intermodal Program--Rail Index |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040906055758/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |archive-date=September 6, 2004|url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the time, the planned Lovejoy line was anticipated to open in 2006 and $106 million in federal funding was earmarked for the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |title=Lovejoy Commuter Rail fact sheet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040302014011/http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |archive-date=September 6, 2004 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Clayton County Board of Commissioners was supportive of the line, asking the state government to advance the plan.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Corriher |first1= Billy |url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/county-requests-atlanta-lovejoy-rail-line/article_7cf4fb09-0fe6-52b9-a3f5-911cb62ade25.html |title=County requests Atlanta-Lovejoy rail line |date=December 16, 2003 |access-date=December 18, 2019 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after years of inaction from the state on the project, then-governor [[Sonny Perdue]] announced his support for the Lovejoy line. This was speculated to be partially due to the project being in danger of losing its federal funding because of a lack of progress.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Saporta |first1= Maria |url=http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |title=At last, Gov. Perdue on board for commuter rail |date=June 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522085502/http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Due to further inaction, the federal government withdrew the funds it had previously appropriated for the project in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simmons |first1=Andria |url=https://www.governing.com/news/headlines/mct-commuter-rail-atlanta.html |title=Feds Take Back Millions in Unused Money for Atlanta Commuter Rail |date=July 11, 2014 |access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Planning by MARTA===\nOn July 5, 2014, the Clayton County Board of Commissioners approved a contract with [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] to extend service to the county by a margin of 3-1, financed by a 1% sales tax. Fulton and DeKalb county leaders approved the expansion and on November 4, 2014, Clayton County residents approved the 1% sales tax to join MARTA. The contract reserves half of the collected tax revenue for the development of rail transit in the county, with the other half funding local bus service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714154106/http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot| archive-date=July 14, 2014 |title=Clayton approves MARTA contract for November ballot |publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta |author=John Ruch |date=2014-07-05}}</ref>\n\nCommuter rail was selected in 2018 as the locally preferred alternative of transit mode along the corridor,<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice >{{cite news |last1=Saporta |first1=Maria |title=Commuter rail is MARTA\u2019s choice for Clayton County |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2018/07/13/commuter-rail-is-marta-s-choice-for-clayton-county.html |accessdate=13 July 2018 |agency=Atlanta Business Journal |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> which was later approved by the MARTA Board of Directors.<ref name=MARTAapproves>{{cite news |last1=Wickert |first1=David |title=MARTA approves plans for Clayton County commuter train |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/marta-approves-plans-for-clayton-county-commuter-train/TGCcz6JGlUOxvzLzQTtUnJ/ |accessdate=8 December 2018 |agency=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, all four MARTA jurisdictions passed the 15th Amendment to the Rapid Transit Contract and Assistance Agreement (RTCAA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itsmarta.com/jurisdictions-pass-15th-amendment.aspx|title=MARTA|website=www.itsmarta.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The amendment enables MARTA to proceed with expansion projects in Clayton County. Exhibit D  Exhibit D, Clayton County System Implantation Plan details several high-capacity transit projects including commuter rail (CRT) and bus rapid transit (BRT).<ref name=\":1\" /> MARTA has committed to continued planning and design on the Clayton County Commuter Rail project, which will stretch 22 miles from East Point Station to Lovejoy, with the first phase (about 11 miles) from East Point to Morrow/Southlake Mall up and running by 2030.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Route==\nThe line follows the existing [[Norfolk Southern]] [[right of way]] from [[East Point station]] to [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] in southern Clayton County, a distance of {{convert|22|mi}}.<ref name=MARTAapproves /> MARTA is negotiating with Norfolk Southern to install tracks in their right of way, adjacent to the freight line.<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice />\n\nOne version of the proposal calls for stations at [[Hapeville, Georgia|Hapeville]], [[Mountain View, Georgia|Mountain View]], [[Forest Park, Georgia|Forest Park]], [[Fort Gillem]], [[Clayton State University]], [[Morrow, Georgia|Morrow]] and [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]]. A station in [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] is also proposed, which would open as a later phase.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |title=MARTA Proposed Clayton County Service in 2025 |access-date=November 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052952/http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.itsmarta.com/clayton-county-overview.aspx MARTA overiew]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MARTA Nav}}\n[[Category:Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rynmrrs", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated overview phraseology to comply with cited sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clayton_County_commuter_rail"}
